,Recommended,531640,29496280,Posted: 25 January,all,Captain Hammer,"See a recommendation below depending on if you've played Magic, Hearthstone, Both, or Neither:MAGIC ONLY:MTG is obviously the foundation of Eternal. The rules are virtually identical. But the game gains two very important qualities over magic: One is the ability to use effects that would be impossible with physical cards. For example, cards in the graveyard (called the ""void"") keep any stats changes applied to them on the battlefield. Some cards affect give permanent +1/+1 to the next unit you draw, etc. Second is the ability to balance these cards if they get out of hand. There won't be a Jace, the Mind Sculptor incident, because these cards aren't in print. They just get patched, and if you don't like the patch changes you can swap it in for any other equivalent rarity card you'd like within a few days. You also don't have to spend money, though you probably used to spending if you're a magic player. It has only one set as of right now, but this one set is a lot more fun and diverse than MTG vanilla was.HEARTHSTONE ONLY:If you've only played Hearthstone, you'll have more cause to hate this game than any of these other groups. Hearthstone uses a system by which you get one mana each turn, with some cards (mostly druid) that let you get more. In this game, you have to draw your mana and play it, max one per turn, as a card from your deck. So what happens if you don't draw any? You get rekt. You lose for no good reason. It's a mechanic pulled over from MTG and it is absolutely infuriating if you haven't built a tolerance to it. Carrying the mana system over from magic without modifying it is probably the biggest mistake the devs made in designing this game. If you sort by negative reviews, this is the theme of almost all of them.On the upside, this game is waaaaay more generous than hearthstone when it comes to earning gold. You can even just play the ""gauntlet"" mode and earn tons of free gold by playing against the AI if you're afraid of your performance vs humans. You know how in HS every three multiplayer wins gets you a tenth of a pack? It's closer to half a pack, plus some cards, in this one. That's not even counting the arena-style modes, which unlike HS let you KEEP the cards you draft and give much nicer rewards without having to win 7+ games in a single run. It really puts the rewards system of hearthstone to shame.BOTH:As someone who put hundreds of hours into both MTG and Hearthstone, I am seriously convinced that Eternal will overtake both of them when it leaves beta. The developers of this game understood some of the core mechanical weaknesses of both of those games (overly complex rules and inability to act on your opponent's turn, respectively) while incorporating many of their strengths. If you enjoy both of these games or have in the past, this might replace both of them. I can't imagine you not liking it.NEITHER:CCGs are a different kind of beast for someone who hasn't played one. They have a lot of variance, which is to say the winner is sometimes a little ""random."" But part of the joy of mastering these games is learning to play within that variance and maximize your chances of winning as many games as possible. It's fun to predict what cards your opponent will likely have in their deck based on what you know about the cards they've played so far, then make plays to counter them. The tutorial (""campaign"") is very long and will help you learn all the basics of games like this. If you're afraid of going up against players with expensive decks, the AI matches are very rewarding and let you build up your own stuff quickly. This is not a simple pay2win iphone-style game where you get clobbered by people with better stuff. I mean, you WILL get clobbered by people with better stuff at first, but you don't have to spend money to ascend to where they are. If this sort of thing sounds up your alley, Eternal is a great first combat card game for you."
